# Documentation Standards

## Documentation File Management

- **NEVER create final documentation files** (_.md, _.mdx, _.rst, _.txt, README.md, etc.)
- If documentation needs to be added or updated, **always modify existing documentation files**
- Search for existing documentation files before making any changes
- Append or update content in existing files rather than creating new ones
- Only create documentation files if explicitly requested by the user

## README Files

- Include clear project description and purpose
- Provide installation and setup instructions
- Document all dependencies and requirements
- Include usage examples and API documentation
- Add troubleshooting section for common issues

## Code Documentation

- Use docstrings for all public functions and classes
- Include parameter types and descriptions
- Document return values and possible exceptions
- Provide usage examples in docstrings
- Keep documentation up-to-date with code changes

## API Documentation

- Document all endpoints and their parameters
- Include request/response examples
- Document authentication requirements
- Specify error codes and their meanings
- Provide rate limiting information if applicable

## Inline Documentation

- Use docstrings instead of comments
- Explain complex business logic
- Document non-obvious implementation decisions
- Include references to external documentation
- Keep documentation concise but comprehensive
